works by filmmakers ranging from J. E. Williamson, inventor of the first undersea film technology in 1914, to Wes Anderson, who filmed the underwater scenes of his 2004 The Life Aquatic with Steve Zissou entirely in a pool, The Underwater Eye traces how the radically alien qualities of underwater optics have shaped liquid fantasies for more than a century. Richly illustrated, the book explores documentaries by Jacques Cousteau, Louis Malle, and Hans Hass, art films by Man Ray and Jean Vigo, and popular movies and television shows such as 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea, Creature from the Black Lagoon, Sea Hunt, the Bond films, Jaws, The Abyss, and Titanic. In exploring the cultural impact of underwater filmmaking, the book also asks compelling questions about the role film plays in engaging the public with the remote ocean, a frontline of climate change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  a000 Leagues Under the Sea.  a20.  aCreature from the Black Lagoon.  aHans Hass.  aHow the Movie Camera Opened the Depths and Unleashed New Realms of Fantasy.  aJ. E. Williamson.  aJacques Cousteau.  aJaws.  aJean Vigo.  aLouis Malle.  aMan Ray.  aMargaret Cohen.  aPrinceton University Press.  aSea Hunt.  aSteve Zissou entirely.  aThe Abyss.  aThe Underwater Eye.  aTitanic.  aWes Anderson.  aaesthetics of movies.  aart films.  aart.  abooks about underwater photography.  achallenge.  achallenging film set on earth.  acinema.  adevelopment of modern diving equipment.  adirecting.  adocumentaries.  aemotional power of the underwater environment.  afilm making.  afilmed the underwater scenes of his 2004 The Life Aquatic.  afilmmakers.  ainventor of the first undersea film technology in 1914.  amovie equipment.  amovie making.  aoc